text: 12/12 Thanks to @dfg_public, @MPC_CompPsych and @mpib_berlin for funding, Michael J Frank @eLife for a pleasant reviewing process and open reviewer @EelkeSpaak for great feedback.
name: Niels Kloosterman

text: 11/12 We programmed mMSE analysis in the format of the @FieldTrip toolbox. A tutorial on mMSE analysis is at https://t.co/4dKHFrARTx. Code to run it is at https://t.co/Yx4vkP4RqK. If you try it, I‚Äôd be curious to hear how it goes
name: Niels Kloosterman

text: 10/12 In summary, we provide first evidence that greater bias shifts are typified in those subjects who exhibit greater shifts in frontal entropy. This suggests that a brain with more irregular moment-to-moment activity can more flexibly adapt to a given environment's constraints
name: Niels Kloosterman

text: 9/12 Post-stim variability decrease (‚Äòquenching‚Äô) has also been proposed to improve cognition by suppressing neural ‚Äònoise‚Äô, despite scarce empirical evidence for behavioral impact. We indeed observed posterior quenching in entropy, but no links with behavior.
name: Niels Kloosterman

text: 8/12 *No* conventional EEG measure of neural activity (SD, power, ERPs) could explain this result. Thus, moment-to-moment neural entropy uniquely tracks bias shifts.
name: Niels Kloosterman

text: 7/12 As expected, we found that subjects who showed a larger liberal bias shift (i.e. more negative criterion difference) were indeed those who also exhibited a larger boost in frontal entropy. The same held within subjects. https://t.co/7K43gorxsT
name: Niels Kloosterman

text: 6/12 Unlike standard MSE, mMSE allows dynamical tracking of variability over time by calculating entropy across discontinuous data segments aggregated across trials via a sliding window approach. This makes entropy analysis suitable for studying transient cognitive operations. https://t.co/ZwR3rzwVD8
name: Niels Kloosterman

text: 5/12 We developed modified multi-scale entropy (mMSE) that measures variability by simply counting repetitions of temporal patterns in the signal. Self-repeating signals such as neural oscillations are assigned lower entropy, whereas more irregular signals yield higher entropy. https://t.co/72ui3K1GPy
name: Niels Kloosterman

text: 4/12 We tested this in our published @eLife dataset involving a continuous target detection task with two different bias manipulations, either emphasizing target detection or avoiding errors. Subjects showed a wide range of decision bias shifts, both across and within subjects. https://t.co/SCMdJ9pptw
name: Niels Kloosterman

text: 3/12 But power could not explain the bias *shift* & show its presumed frontal signature! Entropy might allow brain to keep exploring its dynamical repertoire, become more receptive/response-ready and thus permit the liberal shift. So does frontal entropy then track the shift?
name: Niels Kloosterman

text: 2/12 Shifting decision biases allows one to adapt to the environment: while conservatism avoids errors, a liberal shift helps to detect more targets. We showed previously that band-specific, occipital EEG power enables this bias setting process: https://t.co/t5nGD7GVBy
name: Niels Kloosterman

text:
7/7

Qu 6. What are the team dynamics? Is the PI accessible? Do they support trainee attendance at conferences? Reach-out to other lab members or ask the PI directly. Your PI should appreciate your candid approach. If they don‚Äôt‚Ä¶ you‚Äôll appreciate the early warning.
name: Gregory Day

text:
6/7

Qu 5. How many recent publications include authors at your level of training? Good mentors enable their trainees to achieve their goals. If your goal is to see your work published (with you as first author), ensure that you‚Äôre joining a team where this is expected!
name: Gregory Day

text:
5/7

Qu 4. Does the researcher / mentor have a track record for success? How many publications have they published over the past year? If your time and timeline are limited, you want to know you‚Äôre joining a lab that can deliver if (when) you do.
name: Gregory Day

text:
4/7

Qu 3. Will the work lead to meaningful output (publications, abstracts) regardless of findings? If your goal is to see your work published, be sure you're signing onto a project that will yield useful results... no matter the findings.
name: Gregory Day

text:
3/7

Qu 2. Why is the project available? Best case: the number of good projects in the lab > the number of available researchers. Beware the languishing project or data set. Avoid at all costs learning first-hand why a ‚Äògreat idea‚Äô hasn‚Äôt moved forward for the past 2 years.
name: Gregory Day

text:
2/7

Qu 1. Am I genuinely interested in the project/science? Clinical research almost always requires more time than initially assumed. Genuine interest makes it a whole lot easier to see the project through. When the going gets tough, the interested keep going.
name: Gregory Day
